Plain — Semantics
Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>


EVALUATION MODEL

    Plain evaluates a list of statements left to right. Each statement
    is a node: a keyword followed by zero or more arguments. The walker
    resolves arguments (substituting variables and evaluating nested
    expressions) before looking up the keyword in the frame and invoking
    the bound callable.

    Blocks ({ }) are intentionally deferred — the walker leaves them
    unevaluated so procedures like if and repeat can decide if/when/how
    many times to run them.


STATEMENT vs EXPRESSION

    A statement is a top-level node (no parent). Its return value is
    usually discarded.

    An expression is a node wrapped in [...]. The walker evaluates it
    recursively and substitutes its result as an argument value.

        print [add 1, 2]    ` [add 1, 2] is an expression here


VARIABLES AND FRAMES

    Variables are name-to-value bindings stored in a frame. Frames are
    linked in a chain (lexical scoping): a lookup walks from the innermost
    frame outward until the name is found.

    Assignment is done with = in statement context (no enclosing [...]):

        x = 42
        name = "Plain"

    The = operator cannot be overridden — it is always assignment in
    statement context. Inside [...] it means equality comparison.


CALLABLES

    A callable is a stored function or procedure that can be invoked by
    name, stored in a variable, and passed as an argument.

    Two kinds:

        function   — immutable binding; cannot be reassigned after definition.
        procedure  — mutable binding; can be reassigned at any time.

    Named definition form:

        function  name {parameters} {body}
        procedure name {parameters} {body}

    The name can be a keyword, a quoted string, or an operator symbol:

        function  square {n} { return [n * n] }
        procedure 'greet' {name} { print [join "Hi, ", name] }
        procedure + {a, b} { return [multiply a b] }   ` operator override

    Anonymous (expression) form — returns a callable value:

        double = [function  {n} { return [n * 2] }]
        greet  = [procedure {n} { print [join "Hi, ", n] }]

    The named form does not work when the name is already bound as a
    non-operator variable (the walker resolves the keyword before the
    procedure or function sees it). For rebinding a non-operator name,
    use the expression form:

        double = [function {n} { return [n * 2] }]

    Operator symbol names (+, -, *, etc.) are exempt from this: they are
    never resolved by the walker, so the named form always works for them.


BUILT-IN PROCEDURES

    Built-in procedures (if, repeat, add, etc.) are registered as mutable
    callables in the root frame at startup. Because they are regular
    bindings they can be overridden, stored, passed as arguments, and
    invoked exactly like user-defined callables:

        op = add;
        print [op 3, 4]    ` 7

        add = [procedure {a, b} { return [a + b + 1] }]

    if — condition chains

        if condition {then}
        if condition {then} else {else}
        if condition {then} else condition {then} else condition {then} else {else}

    "else" followed by a block is the final fallback. "else" followed by
    any non-block value is an elseif condition; the chain continues.


INFIX OPERATORS

    The thirteen operator symbols have a special infix calling convention
    when used as the sole argument between a variable name and a value:

        [name op value]

    This is syntactic sugar — it is equivalent to invoking the operator as
    a prefix procedure call with (name_value, value) as arguments:

        [x + 3]    ` same as [+ x 3] once + is bound

    Operator symbols are resolved from the frame at dispatch time, so
    overriding them covers both infix and prefix call sites simultaneously:

        procedure + {a, b} { return [multiply a b] };
        x = 10;
        print [x + 3]    ` 30  (infix, uses override)
        print [+ x 3]    ` 30  (prefix, uses same override)

    The = operator in infix position inside [...] means equality, not
    assignment. The assignment behaviour of = in statement context is
    hardcoded and cannot be overridden.

    Infix is strictly binary. Compound expressions require nesting:

        print [and [x > 0] [x < 10]]


RETURN AND BREAK

    return [value]   exits the current callable and yields a value.
    break            exits the nearest repeat loop.

    Both propagate as special signals through the evaluator.


HOST EXTENSION

    The host application can supply a PLAIN_SUBROUTINE handler on
    PLAIN_CONTEXT that is called for any keyword not found in the frame.
    This is how the Inspector implements print without the library
    containing any I/O.
